#8.
a = [1, 2, 3]
b = [1, 2, 3]
if a is b:
    print("Lists are equal")
--> 'is' --> is an object identifier which checks the memory location. In this code it return none because even 
    Both a and b have the same values defined, but they are stored in different memory locations. Hence, the code returns false, 
    and eventually, it returns None.
